00:01:27.990 --> 00:01:28.000
Yeah. How are we doing it? Um, I can

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:29.830
share screen or I can switch to stream

00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:35.510
view. Probably share screen's easier.

00:01:44.310 --> 00:01:44.320
And do me a favor. Something isn't

00:01:44.320 --> 00:01:45.190
working. I'm going to take the

00:01:45.200 --> 00:01:46.630
headphones off for the talk. So, just

00:01:46.640 --> 00:01:48.550
message me uh on that Discord channel.

00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:51.109
Yeah.

00:01:51.119 --> 00:01:54.069
All right.

00:01:54.079 --> 00:02:07.429
Yeah, sure.

00:02:14.150 --> 00:02:14.160
you say something to me just to test the

00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:14.949
audio.

00:02:14.959 --> 00:02:17.270
>> Mic.

00:02:17.280 --> 00:02:19.830
>> Uh, yeah. Hold on. Let me switch.

00:02:19.840 --> 00:02:20.070
Hopefully,

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:30.790
>> it's choosing the right one. Yep.

00:02:32.309 --> 00:02:32.319
like it.

00:02:32.319 --> 00:02:34.070
>> You say something once more for me.

00:02:34.080 --> 00:02:35.910
>> Test.

00:02:35.920 --> 00:02:38.070
>> Yeah, perfect.

00:02:38.080 --> 00:02:40.229
>> Okay, I'll I'll do a quick introduction

00:02:40.239 --> 00:02:41.990
and then hand over to you in a second.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:52.309
>> Sure.

00:02:54.150 --> 00:02:54.160
>> Hello everyone. Welcome to our our last

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:55.990
talk of the day. I'm very pleased to

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.949
introduce you to Dr. Dr. Joseph Suarez.

00:02:58.959 --> 00:03:02.309
Uh he is the founder of Puffer AI and um

00:03:02.319 --> 00:03:03.910
they work a lot on reinforcement

00:03:03.920 --> 00:03:06.390
learning research. Um and if you

00:03:06.400 --> 00:03:07.750
remember our talk from earlier about

00:03:07.760 --> 00:03:09.589
drones, that's kind of the workforce

00:03:09.599 --> 00:03:12.309
behind uh what we were doing and many of

00:03:12.319 --> 00:03:14.229
the kind of core reinforcement learning

00:03:14.239 --> 00:03:16.949
projects really at the the forefront of

00:03:16.959 --> 00:03:19.430
of research. Um Joseph is going to talk

00:03:19.440 --> 00:03:22.390
to you about um neural MMO which he did

00:03:22.400 --> 00:03:25.910
during his PhD at MIT and also puff as a

00:03:25.920 --> 00:03:27.589
reinforcement learning library in

00:03:27.599 --> 00:03:30.149
general. So I'll hand it over to Joseph

00:03:30.159 --> 00:03:32.550
now. Thank you.

00:03:32.560 --> 00:03:35.430
>> Thanks for the introduction Sam.

00:03:35.440 --> 00:03:43.110
Let me share my screen here.

00:03:46.630 --> 00:03:46.640
This coming through well.

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:50.869
uh do this.

00:03:52.229 --> 00:03:52.239
>> Yep, we're all good.

00:03:52.239 --> 00:03:55.350
>> Cool. I will uh pop these off. You can

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:57.270
let me know if anything's wrong in the

00:03:57.280 --> 00:03:59.750
uh the Discord messages.

00:03:59.760 --> 00:04:07.350
>> Yep, sounds good.

00:04:09.110 --> 00:04:09.120
>> Okay, perfect. Thanks for the

00:04:09.120 --> 00:04:11.910
introduction. Hello everyone. I'm going

00:04:11.920 --> 00:04:14.309
to be talking to you about Whoops, this

00:04:14.319 --> 00:04:17.349
is the wrong slide.

00:04:17.359 --> 00:04:20.150
Let's not give that talk by mistake.

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:24.629
It's a much shorter talk.

00:04:40.550 --> 00:04:40.560
>> Title of the talk today is reinforcement

00:04:40.560 --> 00:04:43.030
learning 10,000 times faster. Uh I'm

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:44.629
going to be talking to you about my work

00:04:44.639 --> 00:04:47.590
on neural MMO from my PhD as well as

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:49.189
what I've been doing in the last couple

00:04:49.199 --> 00:04:50.950
of years on making reinforcement

00:04:50.960 --> 00:04:53.909
learning super fast, super stable,

00:04:53.919 --> 00:04:55.909
broadly accessible, some algorithm work

00:04:55.919 --> 00:04:58.070
as well. And uh it's also just going to

00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:00.710
be the story of a very long project that

00:05:00.720 --> 00:05:03.030
started as something very very far out

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:05.590
there um like way way way off the beaten

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:07.430
path and then eventually came back

00:05:07.440 --> 00:05:09.029
around to being something that is now

00:05:09.039 --> 00:05:11.350
broadly useful. uh really helping people

00:05:11.360 --> 00:05:12.790
get into the field and also being

00:05:12.800 --> 00:05:16.790
deployed uh for companies as well.

00:05:16.800 --> 00:05:19.110
So brief primer, we're not going to get

00:05:19.120 --> 00:05:20.550
too technical. It's mostly about the

00:05:20.560 --> 00:05:22.870
journey and about the tech here. Not

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:24.230
going to get too too deep into the

00:05:24.240 --> 00:05:26.230
details of the RL, but uh for those

00:05:26.240 --> 00:05:30.150
unfamiliar, it is a sub area of AI that

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:32.550
deals with training agents through

00:05:32.560 --> 00:05:33.830
interaction, learning through

00:05:33.840 --> 00:05:35.590
experience. So you have something called

00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:37.670
an environment which is a game, a

00:05:37.680 --> 00:05:39.830
simulator, a robot, anything that can be

00:05:39.840 --> 00:05:41.590
interacted with. And then you have an

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:43.430
agent which is the thing doing the

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:45.430
interacting. And the agent is usually

00:05:45.440 --> 00:05:47.270
parameterized by a neural network. So

00:05:47.280 --> 00:05:48.790
you have a neural network playing a

00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:51.189
game, controlling a robot, uh taking

00:05:51.199 --> 00:05:53.510
actions, making decisions in industrial

00:05:53.520 --> 00:05:57.029
sim. It's very very broad. Uh now before

00:05:57.039 --> 00:05:59.510
we really get started here, just

00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:01.830
something for fun.

00:06:01.840 --> 00:06:03.510
What does it mean to make something 500

00:06:03.520 --> 00:06:06.469
times faster? So, this is a puffer fish.

00:06:06.479 --> 00:06:08.390
Uh, if a puffer fish is really, really

00:06:08.400 --> 00:06:10.469
try and it can swim at 1 to 2 meters per

00:06:10.479 --> 00:06:12.309
second. What does it mean to make

00:06:12.319 --> 00:06:14.550
something 500 times faster? Like, what's

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:17.990
about 500 times faster than this?

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.710
A fighter jet.

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:23.830
So, making something from as fast as a

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:25.590
buffer to as fast as a fighter jet,

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:27.189
that's a pretty darn good improvement,

00:06:27.199 --> 00:06:31.909
right? What about 10,000 times?

00:06:31.919 --> 00:06:33.510
you know, an object that's about 10,000

00:06:33.520 --> 00:06:36.230
times faster than a puffer fish. I was

00:06:36.240 --> 00:06:38.469
thinking, oh, probably a rocket, but

00:06:38.479 --> 00:06:40.469
yeah, those are kind of slow. So, um,

00:06:40.479 --> 00:06:43.110
here's four of them. So, the point of

00:06:43.120 --> 00:06:45.270
this is this is just an absolutely

00:06:45.280 --> 00:06:47.830
ridiculous speed improvement, right?

00:06:47.840 --> 00:06:50.230
Like, you should never be able to make

00:06:50.240 --> 00:06:52.950
anything 10,000 times faster because if

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:54.390
you can, that means that something was

00:06:54.400 --> 00:06:56.950
10,000 times too slow to begin with. And

00:06:56.960 --> 00:06:59.110
really, you should only have to sneeze

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:01.510
at something that is 10,000 times too

00:07:01.520 --> 00:07:03.270
slow to at least make it a little bit

00:07:03.280 --> 00:07:05.670
better. But lo and behold, this was

00:07:05.680 --> 00:07:07.270
actually the case in reinforcement

00:07:07.280 --> 00:07:09.350
learning that it was such a

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:11.909
scientifically dominated field that had

00:07:11.919 --> 00:07:14.150
so little emphasis on the engineering

00:07:14.160 --> 00:07:16.390
that things were legitimately 10,000

00:07:16.400 --> 00:07:18.550
times slower than they could be. Uh, and

00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:20.550
this made it very difficult to actually

00:07:20.560 --> 00:07:22.710
iterate quickly on RL research. I think

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:24.150
it's one of the major reasons you don't

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:26.150
see as much of it as you should see

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:28.390
today and it is now coming back and

00:07:28.400 --> 00:07:29.589
you're seeing a lot more people doing

00:07:29.599 --> 00:07:31.029
stuff because it's way way easier to

00:07:31.039 --> 00:07:33.189
iterate quickly and that has contributed

00:07:33.199 --> 00:07:35.029
to a bunch of algorithmic advancements

00:07:35.039 --> 00:07:36.469
and we're going to talk about all of

00:07:36.479 --> 00:07:39.110
that. But first just one quick little

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:43.510
result demo here. Um this is from my RLC

00:07:43.520 --> 00:07:46.469
talk uh last year and this is training

00:07:46.479 --> 00:07:47.990
breakout. So this is just a little GIF

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:50.629
recorded from my local desktop where we

00:07:50.639 --> 00:07:53.350
trained an agent to play Breakout in

00:07:53.360 --> 00:07:56.710
24ish seconds. So before puffer lib to

00:07:56.720 --> 00:07:58.469
train an agent on breakout you had

00:07:58.479 --> 00:08:00.309
libraries that would take hours or even

00:08:00.319 --> 00:08:02.710
days in order to get even a reasonable

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:05.029
policy. And here you can just train this

00:08:05.039 --> 00:08:06.869
locally, super quick. You know, you have

00:08:06.879 --> 00:08:09.189
an idea, you can try it out, you can try

00:08:09.199 --> 00:08:11.350
another idea. Very, very fast iteration

00:08:11.360 --> 00:08:12.629
cycle. Really, really great for

00:08:12.639 --> 00:08:14.309
research. And then if we watch this

00:08:14.319 --> 00:08:15.990
thing play the game, I've managed to

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:17.430
stall you long enough for the whole

00:08:17.440 --> 00:08:19.909
training to complete. And there you go.

00:08:19.919 --> 00:08:21.350
And you can watch this thing solve the

00:08:21.360 --> 00:08:22.869
entire game. It's several million steps

00:08:22.879 --> 00:08:24.550
per second training, which is already

00:08:24.560 --> 00:08:26.230
around a thousand times faster than what

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:28.150
was out there before. I'll show you at

00:08:28.160 --> 00:08:29.510
the very end of this how we get from

00:08:29.520 --> 00:08:30.950
there to the latest, where now we can

00:08:30.960 --> 00:08:33.269
solve this in just a few seconds. And

00:08:33.279 --> 00:08:35.029
I'll actually demo that live for you if

00:08:35.039 --> 00:08:37.029
we have time. Uh, but this is a nice

00:08:37.039 --> 00:08:39.190
little starting point. But of course,

00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:40.630
the point of reinforcement learning is

00:08:40.640 --> 00:08:42.230
not just to solve breakout. It's to

00:08:42.240 --> 00:08:43.829
solve a wide variety of problems, right?

00:08:43.839 --> 00:08:45.350
We just like these games because they're

00:08:45.360 --> 00:08:46.870
quick, they're interpretable, and they

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:48.310
let us get a lot of the infrastructure

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:50.710
right. And a lot of my work has dealt

00:08:50.720 --> 00:08:52.550
with how do we make reinforcement

00:08:52.560 --> 00:08:55.269
learning useful in large complex

00:08:55.279 --> 00:08:56.790
environments where we can ask hard

00:08:56.800 --> 00:08:59.590
questions and uh study what is needed

00:08:59.600 --> 00:09:03.829
for this sub area of AI to advance.

00:09:03.839 --> 00:09:05.910
Now this project started a long time ago

00:09:05.920 --> 00:09:08.310
probably around 2017. I was thinking

00:09:08.320 --> 00:09:09.829
about it even a little bit before that

00:09:09.839 --> 00:09:11.509
and the really the relevant questions

00:09:11.519 --> 00:09:13.509
back then were what is the right

00:09:13.519 --> 00:09:15.509
environment for studying intelligence

00:09:15.519 --> 00:09:17.990
for making contributions creating better

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:21.590
algorithms and then how do we build it?

00:09:21.600 --> 00:09:23.110
It was pretty obvious even back then

00:09:23.120 --> 00:09:24.389
that you wanted something that should be

00:09:24.399 --> 00:09:25.829
computationally efficient and

00:09:25.839 --> 00:09:27.750
interpretable. So you need a simulator

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:29.110
that can run quickly and that you can

00:09:29.120 --> 00:09:31.590
tell what is going on.

00:09:31.600 --> 00:09:33.829
You also want something realistic, but

00:09:33.839 --> 00:09:35.590
going too far down the path of realism

00:09:35.600 --> 00:09:37.509
is actually a bit of a trap because it's

00:09:37.519 --> 00:09:39.269
hard to make something that is fast and

00:09:39.279 --> 00:09:41.509
realistic. So, what you end up wanting

00:09:41.519 --> 00:09:43.990
is actually cognitive realism. You want

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.230
something that behaves in roughly the

00:09:46.240 --> 00:09:48.070
same manner as the real world at an

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:49.750
intellectual level that poses the same

00:09:49.760 --> 00:09:52.150
types of challenges in exploration and

00:09:52.160 --> 00:09:53.750
credit assignment. And if you were to

00:09:53.760 --> 00:09:55.110
sort of break down the things that make

00:09:55.120 --> 00:09:56.949
problems hard, you want a lot of those

00:09:56.959 --> 00:09:58.790
same challenges to be present in

00:09:58.800 --> 00:10:01.990
whatever environment you build.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:03.829
So when I was first starting this work,

00:10:03.839 --> 00:10:05.269
I started building some stuff. It was

00:10:05.279 --> 00:10:07.190
2017 and you know within the next couple

00:10:07.200 --> 00:10:08.949
of years around there, that's when the

00:10:08.959 --> 00:10:10.710
big labs were starting to scale up

00:10:10.720 --> 00:10:12.790
reinforcement learning. You had open AI

00:10:12.800 --> 00:10:15.509
with Dota. You had um Deep Mind with

00:10:15.519 --> 00:10:18.230
Alph Go and solving Starcraft, Alpha

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:19.829
Star. You also had these somewhat

00:10:19.839 --> 00:10:21.910
lesserk known but still pretty out there

00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:23.670
projects, emerging tool use and capture

00:10:23.680 --> 00:10:25.509
the flag. And really the idea was we're

00:10:25.519 --> 00:10:26.790
just going to scale up reinforcement

00:10:26.800 --> 00:10:27.910
learning. We're going to see what's

00:10:27.920 --> 00:10:29.110
possible. we're going to solve some

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:31.030
really hard games and we're going to see

00:10:31.040 --> 00:10:32.790
where that goes. And they got some

00:10:32.800 --> 00:10:35.030
tremendously impressive results, some of

00:10:35.040 --> 00:10:36.550
which still have not been surpassed to

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:39.670
this day. Uh, but for my own work, most

00:10:39.680 --> 00:10:41.110
of these environments are not open

00:10:41.120 --> 00:10:44.470
source. And even if they were, they're

00:10:44.480 --> 00:10:46.790
very slow. Like you need a thousand GPUs

00:10:46.800 --> 00:10:48.550
to even do anything. You're not going to

00:10:48.560 --> 00:10:50.069
be able to quickly tweak things and see,

00:10:50.079 --> 00:10:51.750
oh, what if the agent has to do this?

00:10:51.760 --> 00:10:53.990
What if it has to use that? So this was

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.550
just like far too large for the types of

00:10:56.560 --> 00:10:59.190
stuff that I was interested in. So I

00:10:59.200 --> 00:11:01.430
decided to make my own environment. And

00:11:01.440 --> 00:11:04.470
I landed on the idea of using massively

00:11:04.480 --> 00:11:07.350
multiplayer online games as the basis

00:11:07.360 --> 00:11:09.430
for inspiration.

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:10.870
And the reason for this, if you're not

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:13.269
familiar with the genre, is that this is

00:11:13.279 --> 00:11:16.230
just a perfect storm for um you end up

00:11:16.240 --> 00:11:17.750
with this genre of games that was

00:11:17.760 --> 00:11:19.829
optimized to run cities of players on

00:11:19.839 --> 00:11:21.829
'90s hardware. So way more

00:11:21.839 --> 00:11:23.269
computationally efficient than other

00:11:23.279 --> 00:11:25.030
genres and at the same time they were

00:11:25.040 --> 00:11:26.630
still interesting for people to play.

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:28.470
It's not like they were trivial, right?

00:11:28.480 --> 00:11:31.750
You'd end up with emergent economies,

00:11:31.760 --> 00:11:33.590
forces of supply and demand,

00:11:33.600 --> 00:11:36.230
specialization to different skills, both

00:11:36.240 --> 00:11:37.990
in terms of the players being good at

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:39.670
different things and also them

00:11:39.680 --> 00:11:41.670
optimizing their characters to be geared

00:11:41.680 --> 00:11:43.670
out for specific things. And then you

00:11:43.680 --> 00:11:45.590
get cooperation and competition among

00:11:45.600 --> 00:11:47.829
players. Really a very sophisticated

00:11:47.839 --> 00:11:50.470
sort of world set. Um, I actually credit

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:52.949
most of my ideas in reinforcement

00:11:52.959 --> 00:11:54.870
learning directly to a deep

00:11:54.880 --> 00:11:56.870
understanding of how a lot of these

00:11:56.880 --> 00:11:59.110
games were built back in the 90s and the

00:11:59.120 --> 00:12:00.389
types of tricks that were used to

00:12:00.399 --> 00:12:03.110
introduce interesting gameplay on a

00:12:03.120 --> 00:12:06.470
tight computational budget.

00:12:06.480 --> 00:12:07.910
So, I decided to build my own

00:12:07.920 --> 00:12:10.310
environment that was largely inspired by

00:12:10.320 --> 00:12:11.990
MMOs. There were some other things

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:13.990
floating around at the time. Artificial

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:16.629
life was very big back then. So, how do

00:12:16.639 --> 00:12:19.670
we take inspiration from survival and

00:12:19.680 --> 00:12:23.829
from like natural ecology and um you

00:12:23.839 --> 00:12:26.310
know these sorts of things? So, it was

00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:28.150
kind of a mix at first, but that was the

00:12:28.160 --> 00:12:30.550
idea. Let's just put as much interesting

00:12:30.560 --> 00:12:32.870
stuff as possible into one fast

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:34.550
environment that you can run at home,

00:12:34.560 --> 00:12:36.069
have a bunch of agents, a lot of

00:12:36.079 --> 00:12:37.829
different types of interactions, and see

00:12:37.839 --> 00:12:39.509
what types of things we can study in

00:12:39.519 --> 00:12:41.990
that setting and not need a thousand

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.230
GPUs to run it.

00:12:44.240 --> 00:12:45.750
So, the first part of this is really

00:12:45.760 --> 00:12:47.350
going to be about the process of

00:12:47.360 --> 00:12:49.190
building this. And this is something

00:12:49.200 --> 00:12:51.829
that I spent years and years on. And I

00:12:51.839 --> 00:12:53.110
sort of want to share with you a little

00:12:53.120 --> 00:12:55.110
bit of what went on behind the scenes

00:12:55.120 --> 00:12:57.190
there. Because in these very long form

00:12:57.200 --> 00:12:58.629
projects, when you're doing something

00:12:58.639 --> 00:13:01.910
that's very, very far out left field,

00:13:01.920 --> 00:13:03.750
the right questions to ask are not

00:13:03.760 --> 00:13:06.069
obvious. And often times you go down

00:13:06.079 --> 00:13:07.990
lots of rabbit holes answering the wrong

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:09.590
questions or answering the right

00:13:09.600 --> 00:13:11.509
questions in the wrong way. And I want

00:13:11.519 --> 00:13:12.790
to share a little bit of what that looks

00:13:12.800 --> 00:13:14.629
like and how difficult this process is.

00:13:14.639 --> 00:13:16.389
But then ultimately this all comes back

00:13:16.399 --> 00:13:17.910
to make it possible to do what I did

00:13:17.920 --> 00:13:19.750
today with Puffer where now this stuff

00:13:19.760 --> 00:13:22.150
just works. It works broadly and I know

00:13:22.160 --> 00:13:23.509
for a fact that it's going to continue

00:13:23.519 --> 00:13:25.030
to work as we scale it up to more

00:13:25.040 --> 00:13:26.949
complex environments because I built one

00:13:26.959 --> 00:13:30.150
of the most complex ones out there.

00:13:30.160 --> 00:13:32.230
This is the earliest screenshot I could

00:13:32.240 --> 00:13:34.550
find. Uh the first sort of commit I made

00:13:34.560 --> 00:13:36.949
in 2017. I really didn't know what I was

00:13:36.959 --> 00:13:38.629
doing back then at all. I decided to do

00:13:38.639 --> 00:13:40.550
it anyways. I sort of had this core idea

00:13:40.560 --> 00:13:43.190
that okay, MMOs are interesting, AI is

00:13:43.200 --> 00:13:44.790
interesting. I wasn't even doing proper

00:13:44.800 --> 00:13:47.430
RL back then, but I did it anyways and I

00:13:47.440 --> 00:13:48.550
wanted to share some of these early

00:13:48.560 --> 00:13:50.069
screenshots.

00:13:50.079 --> 00:13:53.030
So, this was the first prototype I made.

00:13:53.040 --> 00:13:55.350
Uh, you can see it's just awful knockoff

00:13:55.360 --> 00:13:57.990
Minecraft. And this was completely the

00:13:58.000 --> 00:13:59.189
wrong environment. It turns out

00:13:59.199 --> 00:14:01.269
Minecraft is a very bad environment for

00:14:01.279 --> 00:14:03.189
this type of RL work. I tried to get

00:14:03.199 --> 00:14:04.790
some agents running around chopping down

00:14:04.800 --> 00:14:07.189
trees. It was super slow. it was way too

00:14:07.199 --> 00:14:08.790
complicated for what I needed and it

00:14:08.800 --> 00:14:10.069
didn't have the complexities in the

00:14:10.079 --> 00:14:12.949
right areas that you didn't need. So I

00:14:12.959 --> 00:14:14.470
went back to square one and I ended up

00:14:14.480 --> 00:14:21.990
with something sort of like this.

00:14:23.750 --> 00:14:23.760
So in this environment, it's a much

00:14:23.760 --> 00:14:25.590
simpler setting, but we got agents that

00:14:25.600 --> 00:14:27.110
need food, they need water, so they need

00:14:27.120 --> 00:14:29.430
these two resources to survive. And they

00:14:29.440 --> 00:14:30.550
were able to learn these sort of

00:14:30.560 --> 00:14:32.629
cyclical foraging patterns where they

00:14:32.639 --> 00:14:34.150
would go back and forth between food and

00:14:34.160 --> 00:14:36.230
water. This wasn't even RL at first. It

00:14:36.240 --> 00:14:38.069
was just very simple genetic algorithms,

00:14:38.079 --> 00:14:39.670
but it was something. We could put a lot

00:14:39.680 --> 00:14:41.829
of agents into an environment. We had a

00:14:41.839 --> 00:14:43.670
way that we could see what was going on.

00:14:43.680 --> 00:14:44.870
We could start introducing more

00:14:44.880 --> 00:14:46.230
mechanics. We could load in different

00:14:46.240 --> 00:14:49.430
maps. This was the start of it. So, I

00:14:49.440 --> 00:14:50.790
continued building this out a little

00:14:50.800 --> 00:14:52.870
bit. You can see on the left I was

00:14:52.880 --> 00:14:54.230
playing around with, well, what if

00:14:54.240 --> 00:14:55.590
there's a market that they can buy and

00:14:55.600 --> 00:14:57.350
sell things? What if they're like

00:14:57.360 --> 00:14:58.949
enemies, chickens and goblins and

00:14:58.959 --> 00:15:00.069
things? You can sort of see the little

00:15:00.079 --> 00:15:01.910
pixelated characters that they can

00:15:01.920 --> 00:15:03.750
fight. just introducing some additional

00:15:03.760 --> 00:15:05.350
complexities to see what would happen.

00:15:05.360 --> 00:15:08.629
It was very exploratory at first and

00:15:08.639 --> 00:15:10.230
what if we have other maps that they can

00:15:10.240 --> 00:15:11.910
use to sort of introduce different types

00:15:11.920 --> 00:15:13.910
of exploration challenges in what do

00:15:13.920 --> 00:15:17.269
they learn then? So around this time uh

00:15:17.279 --> 00:15:21.430
OpenAI was doing their Dota 1 v1s and I

00:15:21.440 --> 00:15:23.750
ended up going there for about six

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:26.470
months as an intern to really work on

00:15:26.480 --> 00:15:29.509
making this full first version of neural

00:15:29.519 --> 00:15:30.870
MMO. They were thinking a lot about

00:15:30.880 --> 00:15:32.629
different RL environments and it was

00:15:32.639 --> 00:15:33.990
just the perfect place to build this

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:35.670
type of stuff. So this is one of the

00:15:35.680 --> 00:15:37.110
very early renders that I believe I

00:15:37.120 --> 00:15:39.509
built while I was there. And you can see

00:15:39.519 --> 00:15:41.509
we have now an isometric render. There's

00:15:41.519 --> 00:15:43.509
also a top down toggle. You can see

00:15:43.519 --> 00:15:45.110
there's a little bit more of the stacks

00:15:45.120 --> 00:15:47.189
from before expanded. And on the right

00:15:47.199 --> 00:15:48.470
there's actually this little command

00:15:48.480 --> 00:15:49.829
console where you could type in

00:15:49.839 --> 00:15:51.749
different things or hit different keys

00:15:51.759 --> 00:15:52.629
and you would get different

00:15:52.639 --> 00:15:54.150
visualizations

00:15:54.160 --> 00:15:55.829
uh overlaid on top of the environment

00:15:55.839 --> 00:15:57.990
that you'll see later. And this was kind

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.030
of co-designing a visualization toolkit

00:16:01.040 --> 00:16:02.470
with an environment. So we could

00:16:02.480 --> 00:16:04.550
simultaneously iterate on building an

00:16:04.560 --> 00:16:06.389
interesting environment and visualizing

00:16:06.399 --> 00:16:07.990
what on earth these agents are actually

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:11.189
learning.

00:16:13.350 --> 00:16:13.360
This was the first public version that I

00:16:13.360 --> 00:16:15.829
released. This was neural 1.0. You'll

00:16:15.839 --> 00:16:17.509
see that the graphics will swap around a

00:16:17.519 --> 00:16:19.590
whole bunch throughout uh the course of

00:16:19.600 --> 00:16:21.269
this. It's not just to make it look

00:16:21.279 --> 00:16:23.350
fancier. It's also because it's really

00:16:23.360 --> 00:16:25.430
tough to know what's going on a lot of

00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:27.269
the time. You know, these are not people

00:16:27.279 --> 00:16:28.790
playing a game doing what you'd expect

00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:30.870
people to be doing. Agents discover all

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:32.790
sorts of weird stuff and it's not always

00:16:32.800 --> 00:16:34.310
clear if the agent is doing something

00:16:34.320 --> 00:16:35.990
correct or if there's something wrong

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:37.990
with the environment, right? So, you

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:39.990
need a lot of ability to visualize stuff

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.069
and that was sort of a major finding

00:16:42.079 --> 00:16:43.670
early on is when you start scaling up

00:16:43.680 --> 00:16:45.350
environment complexity, you actually

00:16:45.360 --> 00:16:47.350
need a way better interpretability

00:16:47.360 --> 00:16:49.110
toolkit.

00:16:49.120 --> 00:16:51.509
Um, so the initial environment it had

00:16:51.519 --> 00:16:53.749
food and water forging from before and

00:16:53.759 --> 00:16:55.430
also agents could fight each other with

00:16:55.440 --> 00:16:57.749
a few different combat styles. This was

00:16:57.759 --> 00:16:59.590
very simple, but it was actually much

00:16:59.600 --> 00:17:01.110
more complex than most of what was out

00:17:01.120 --> 00:17:03.509
there in multi-agent reinforcement

00:17:03.519 --> 00:17:05.029
learning and particularly for

00:17:05.039 --> 00:17:06.710
multi-agent RL that you could actually

00:17:06.720 --> 00:17:11.189
run on one computer.

00:17:13.429 --> 00:17:13.439
This was the initial graphic. This is

00:17:13.439 --> 00:17:14.630
what it looked like with the agents

00:17:14.640 --> 00:17:16.230
running around. These are some trained

00:17:16.240 --> 00:17:18.230
agents. They could learn to explore the

00:17:18.240 --> 00:17:19.510
map. They could learn to forge for

00:17:19.520 --> 00:17:21.510
resources. They would fight each other.

00:17:21.520 --> 00:17:23.110
Pretty basic, but already kind of fun to

00:17:23.120 --> 00:17:26.309
watch.

00:17:27.829 --> 00:17:27.839
We also had a lot of work on these

00:17:27.839 --> 00:17:29.909
static maps early on. This is one of the

00:17:29.919 --> 00:17:32.150
things where it really wasn't clear what

00:17:32.160 --> 00:17:34.630
was the correct like setup for these.

00:17:34.640 --> 00:17:36.710
So, one of the initial ideas was, well,

00:17:36.720 --> 00:17:38.150
what if we make a lot of different maps

00:17:38.160 --> 00:17:39.750
that pose different exploration

00:17:39.760 --> 00:17:41.990
challenges? So, in this one, the idea

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:43.990
was that there is water, there is food,

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:45.590
and the agents have to ping pong back

00:17:45.600 --> 00:17:47.669
and forth between food and water as they

00:17:47.679 --> 00:17:49.909
explore the map. And we did actually get

00:17:49.919 --> 00:17:51.590
this to work where the agents would all

00:17:51.600 --> 00:17:53.430
start off in the north of the map, and

00:17:53.440 --> 00:17:54.710
they would get pretty much all the way

00:17:54.720 --> 00:17:56.390
to the bottom. They wouldn't cover the

00:17:56.400 --> 00:17:58.549
entire thing. Uh, but what we realized

00:17:58.559 --> 00:18:00.710
was ultimately it was pretty hard to

00:18:00.720 --> 00:18:02.870
train agents on just one map. There

00:18:02.880 --> 00:18:05.350
really just isn't that much signal. You

00:18:05.360 --> 00:18:07.029
kind of need them to see more different

00:18:07.039 --> 00:18:09.110
things during training. So we ended up

00:18:09.120 --> 00:18:10.710
realizing that you needed to randomize

00:18:10.720 --> 00:18:12.710
the maps at least a bit during training.

00:18:12.720 --> 00:18:13.990
And that's what we did for the first

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.070
release. Uh we shipped randomly

00:18:16.080 --> 00:18:18.230
generated maps, a nice little training

00:18:18.240 --> 00:18:19.669
setup so that you could create some

00:18:19.679 --> 00:18:22.630
agents and some visualization tools for

00:18:22.640 --> 00:18:24.310
researchers to use to just explore this

00:18:24.320 --> 00:18:26.789
stuff generally.

00:18:26.799 --> 00:18:28.950
After that I finished up my undergrad. I

00:18:28.960 --> 00:18:31.350
started my PhD and I started working on

00:18:31.360 --> 00:18:34.549
this more seriously. And uh at that

00:18:34.559 --> 00:18:36.390
time, right, it was mostly like, let's

00:18:36.400 --> 00:18:38.630
just get this pop tool, get polished up.

00:18:38.640 --> 00:18:41.110
Um we can sort of see that it's working,

00:18:41.120 --> 00:18:42.870
but stuff is still pretty fiddly. It's

00:18:42.880 --> 00:18:44.390
still pretty hard to use. You can't

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:46.630
always tell exactly what's going on. So,

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:48.390
we started just iterating on the

00:18:48.400 --> 00:18:50.870
platform itself quite a bit. And one of

00:18:50.880 --> 00:18:52.470
the first things I remember adding in

00:18:52.480 --> 00:18:54.950
was some sort of persistent progression

00:18:54.960 --> 00:18:56.630
where agents could level up their

00:18:56.640 --> 00:18:58.710
ability to gather food and gather water.

00:18:58.720 --> 00:19:00.630
They could level up their combat skills.

00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:02.150
And this would make it so that agents

00:19:02.160 --> 00:19:04.150
would be stronger later on. So it wasn't

00:19:04.160 --> 00:19:06.070
so homogeneous, right? It wasn't just

00:19:06.080 --> 00:19:08.390
always the same types of behaviors.

00:19:08.400 --> 00:19:09.430
There's actually a little bit of

00:19:09.440 --> 00:19:11.110
decision-making that had to go into it

00:19:11.120 --> 00:19:12.870
based on what other agents were around,

00:19:12.880 --> 00:19:14.710
how strong you were, how they were, and

00:19:14.720 --> 00:19:16.470
the like.

00:19:16.480 --> 00:19:17.990
Now, this is one spot that I want to

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:19.990
pause on, not to explain this figure

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:21.350
because this is just a really fancy

00:19:21.360 --> 00:19:23.350
neural net architecture, but to kind of

00:19:23.360 --> 00:19:25.830
explain why I had figures like this at

00:19:25.840 --> 00:19:28.710
all. And this goes back to the idea of

00:19:28.720 --> 00:19:29.990
when you're doing something very far out

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:32.150
in left field, it's not even clear what

00:19:32.160 --> 00:19:33.750
the right questions are that you should

00:19:33.760 --> 00:19:36.390
be asking. And back then, one of the

00:19:36.400 --> 00:19:38.470
questions was, well, how on earth do we

00:19:38.480 --> 00:19:40.390
design neural networks for these things?

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:42.390
Because we have a big blob of game data

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:44.310
on the input side, and then there's a

00:19:44.320 --> 00:19:46.230
big blob of action data on the output

00:19:46.240 --> 00:19:48.470
side, and these don't fit nicely with

00:19:48.480 --> 00:19:50.549
your standard neural net architectures

00:19:50.559 --> 00:19:53.029
at all. It's very structured data, and

00:19:53.039 --> 00:19:54.549
we have to come up with networks to

00:19:54.559 --> 00:19:56.789
figure out how to handle that. and they

00:19:56.799 --> 00:19:58.390
would get very very large and very

00:19:58.400 --> 00:20:00.310
fiddly. If you want a really crazy

00:20:00.320 --> 00:20:02.630
example of that, check uh go look up the

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:05.110
uh the OpenA5 Dota architecture. It's

00:20:05.120 --> 00:20:07.750
nuts. So, I came up with something that

00:20:07.760 --> 00:20:10.070
I thought was at least pretty decent

00:20:10.080 --> 00:20:12.950
that let you specify all of the objects

00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:14.150
in the environment that you could

00:20:14.160 --> 00:20:15.909
observe and they could all have a bunch

00:20:15.919 --> 00:20:17.270
of different properties and it would

00:20:17.280 --> 00:20:18.630
give you a way to sort of crunch them

00:20:18.640 --> 00:20:20.470
all down into something that you could

00:20:20.480 --> 00:20:22.549
put into a neural network. But this was

00:20:22.559 --> 00:20:24.630
ultimately a ton of work. it was super

00:20:24.640 --> 00:20:27.110
slow and this was such a pain that

00:20:27.120 --> 00:20:29.430
nowadays I actually just designed the

00:20:29.440 --> 00:20:31.270
environments a little bit differently

00:20:31.280 --> 00:20:32.630
where they can do the same thing

00:20:32.640 --> 00:20:34.310
internally but the data that they send

00:20:34.320 --> 00:20:35.909
to the agent just doesn't look like this

00:20:35.919 --> 00:20:37.430
because I know what a pain it is to deal

00:20:37.440 --> 00:20:38.950
with. So that's kind of like one of

00:20:38.960 --> 00:20:40.789
those things that early on you really

00:20:40.799 --> 00:20:42.230
don't know whether you need to solve

00:20:42.240 --> 00:20:43.590
this problem or if there's a way around

00:20:43.600 --> 00:20:45.669
it. Ultimately we found a way around it

00:20:45.679 --> 00:20:47.590
but this workound at least was enough to

00:20:47.600 --> 00:20:51.669
power a couple years worth of research.

00:20:51.679 --> 00:20:53.830
Neural kept advancing. It kept getting

00:20:53.840 --> 00:20:57.270
more complex. You'll see a quick demo of

00:20:57.280 --> 00:21:00.310
behaviors in here, I believe. Yeah. So,

00:21:00.320 --> 00:21:01.590
this is the policies that we were

00:21:01.600 --> 00:21:03.270
training maybe a couple years into my

00:21:03.280 --> 00:21:05.830
PhD. We had agents that would explore

00:21:05.840 --> 00:21:07.669
the maps. The maps got a little bit

00:21:07.679 --> 00:21:09.590
larger and more complex. The agents

00:21:09.600 --> 00:21:11.270
could level up. Now, that made it a lot

00:21:11.280 --> 00:21:12.549
harder because they had to think about,

00:21:12.559 --> 00:21:15.110
okay, am I strong? Am I weak? Um, there

00:21:15.120 --> 00:21:16.630
was a lot of complexity introduced by

00:21:16.640 --> 00:21:18.950
that. And it was pretty stable. And the

00:21:18.960 --> 00:21:20.230
thing I was really happy about is that

00:21:20.240 --> 00:21:21.510
you actually had a good idea of what

00:21:21.520 --> 00:21:22.950
agents were learning and what they were

00:21:22.960 --> 00:21:25.590
doing, which was quite rare at the time.

00:21:25.600 --> 00:21:27.029
So you could see exactly where all the

00:21:27.039 --> 00:21:29.190
agents have been splatted right directly

00:21:29.200 --> 00:21:31.510
into this renderer.

00:21:31.520 --> 00:21:33.750
And then you could also see uh you could

00:21:33.760 --> 00:21:35.190
reach into the agents and see whether

00:21:35.200 --> 00:21:36.390
they thought that their position was

00:21:36.400 --> 00:21:38.470
good or bad. And you could even smooth

00:21:38.480 --> 00:21:40.070
it over the entire map and see, ah,

00:21:40.080 --> 00:21:41.350
okay, they've learned correctly that

00:21:41.360 --> 00:21:44.070
they should be near food and near water.

00:21:44.080 --> 00:21:45.909
And you could go watch the agents. You

00:21:45.919 --> 00:21:47.669
could say, "Okay, they're fighting.

00:21:47.679 --> 00:21:49.430
going to go get some food, going to go

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:51.350
get some water. Cool. That looks

00:21:51.360 --> 00:21:53.990
reasonable. And for comparison, the

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:55.590
untrained policies, it's very, very

00:21:55.600 --> 00:21:56.789
obvious they've learned something

00:21:56.799 --> 00:21:58.549
reasonable. This is what happens if you

00:21:58.559 --> 00:22:01.669
just behave randomly.

00:22:01.679 --> 00:22:03.110
So, we continued building this thing out

00:22:03.120 --> 00:22:05.110
as a benchmark. We kept writing papers

00:22:05.120 --> 00:22:06.710
on, okay, this is the latest version.

00:22:06.720 --> 00:22:08.149
These are the features. These are the

00:22:08.159 --> 00:22:09.350
some of the things that we've seen the

00:22:09.360 --> 00:22:11.110
agents doing. These are some of the new

00:22:11.120 --> 00:22:12.390
questions that we're thinking about with

00:22:12.400 --> 00:22:14.070
the latest version, with the new stuff

00:22:14.080 --> 00:22:15.909
that's in the environment. We started

00:22:15.919 --> 00:22:17.590
introducing like an achievement system

00:22:17.600 --> 00:22:19.430
where they could make progress along

00:22:19.440 --> 00:22:22.230
different axes. Um, we started trying to

00:22:22.240 --> 00:22:23.990
like figure out if we could put multiple

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:25.990
policies into the same environment. Lots

00:22:26.000 --> 00:22:28.789
of things like this.

00:22:28.799 --> 00:22:31.110
We also made it a lot larger. So the

00:22:31.120 --> 00:22:33.909
maps could be up to a,000 by a,000 which

00:22:33.919 --> 00:22:35.270
would take them 10 minutes to walk

00:22:35.280 --> 00:22:37.270
across. Much more persistent

00:22:37.280 --> 00:22:39.350
progression.

00:22:39.360 --> 00:22:41.110
And even the smaller maps that we would

00:22:41.120 --> 00:22:42.390
use for experiments, we made a little

00:22:42.400 --> 00:22:44.070
bit larger. So we could really see,

00:22:44.080 --> 00:22:45.830
okay, know they're learning to cover an

00:22:45.840 --> 00:22:48.549
entire reasonable map. On the big maps,

00:22:48.559 --> 00:22:54.230
they would cover a good chunk of it.

00:22:56.070 --> 00:22:56.080
Once all this was pretty stable, we

00:22:56.080 --> 00:22:57.430
started looking for ways to make the

00:22:57.440 --> 00:22:58.950
environment more complex and interesting

00:22:58.960 --> 00:23:00.230
because that really doesn't look too

00:23:00.240 --> 00:23:01.990
much like an MMO yet, right? There's not

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:04.549
really the like the different skills,

00:23:04.559 --> 00:23:06.070
um, the different progressions, the

00:23:06.080 --> 00:23:08.149
different specializations. So, this was

00:23:08.159 --> 00:23:11.270
what we wanted to introduce next.

00:23:11.280 --> 00:23:13.029
And the idea was just to add in an

00:23:13.039 --> 00:23:15.750
equipment system, an inventory system, a

00:23:15.760 --> 00:23:17.510
bunch of new professions, a bunch of new

00:23:17.520 --> 00:23:19.590
resources to gather where agents could

00:23:19.600 --> 00:23:21.590
run around the map. They could level up

00:23:21.600 --> 00:23:23.909
like a mining skill, a fishing skill, a

00:23:23.919 --> 00:23:26.070
few other skills, and they could get

00:23:26.080 --> 00:23:28.149
higher and higher quality resources by

00:23:28.159 --> 00:23:29.990
doing that. And then they could sell and

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:31.590
buy resources with each other on a

00:23:31.600 --> 00:23:33.029
global market. So they could make their

00:23:33.039 --> 00:23:34.870
own little economy. There were weapons,

00:23:34.880 --> 00:23:36.630
there were different ammunitions, all

00:23:36.640 --> 00:23:38.070
sorts of different things that all sort

00:23:38.080 --> 00:23:40.070
of fed into each other. And you know,

00:23:40.080 --> 00:23:41.350
you always needed something that

00:23:41.360 --> 00:23:42.870
somebody else had and you always had

00:23:42.880 --> 00:23:46.630
something that somebody else wanted.

00:23:46.640 --> 00:23:48.630
So we had this question of, well, is it

00:23:48.640 --> 00:23:50.230
actually good to specialize, right? Is

00:23:50.240 --> 00:23:52.390
there a reason to make use of a specific

00:23:52.400 --> 00:23:54.390
one of these or are all the agents just

00:23:54.400 --> 00:23:55.750
going to always be wanting to do the

00:23:55.760 --> 00:23:57.830
same thing? And we found that actually

00:23:57.840 --> 00:23:59.590
very quickly when you introduce any sort

00:23:59.600 --> 00:24:01.909
of system like this, specialization is a

00:24:01.919 --> 00:24:04.070
pretty natural thing that just becomes

00:24:04.080 --> 00:24:06.630
incentivized. Um, even with some very

00:24:06.640 --> 00:24:09.350
simple scripted agents, we found that

00:24:09.360 --> 00:24:11.029
going around and just gathering all the

00:24:11.039 --> 00:24:14.230
resources nearby is a worse strategy

00:24:14.240 --> 00:24:16.230
than seeking out a specific type of

00:24:16.240 --> 00:24:18.070
resource, leveling up the skill

00:24:18.080 --> 00:24:19.990
associated with it, and then being able

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:22.390
to sell very high quality items from

00:24:22.400 --> 00:24:25.350
that specific skill. So, it's better to

00:24:25.360 --> 00:24:26.950
be able to have a specialty, sell stuff

00:24:26.960 --> 00:24:28.549
in your specialty, and just buy

00:24:28.559 --> 00:24:29.990
everything that you need from other

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.310
specialists. And this ends up better for

00:24:32.320 --> 00:24:34.310
everybody. Like all the agents in the

00:24:34.320 --> 00:24:35.909
simulation when you do this end up with

00:24:35.919 --> 00:24:37.430
better equipment, better tools, better

00:24:37.440 --> 00:24:39.510
stuff overall. So I was very happy with

00:24:39.520 --> 00:24:41.909
this result. It kind of showed that the

00:24:41.919 --> 00:24:43.430
simulation at least in principle when

00:24:43.440 --> 00:24:45.269
you build stuff like this, you do

00:24:45.279 --> 00:24:46.950
incentivize some things that we care

00:24:46.960 --> 00:24:48.950
about seeing uh in the real world,

00:24:48.960 --> 00:24:50.870
right? Specialization and

00:24:50.880 --> 00:24:54.070
diversification of skills and so on. So

00:24:54.080 --> 00:24:56.870
this made it into neural 2.0, 0 which

00:24:56.880 --> 00:24:58.310
was the last major version that we

00:24:58.320 --> 00:25:00.789
published during my PhD as a data set

00:25:00.799 --> 00:25:02.870
and benchmark.

00:25:02.880 --> 00:25:04.549
This was the environment. We did a whole

00:25:04.559 --> 00:25:06.149
bunch of work on the back end of this as

00:25:06.159 --> 00:25:08.230
well. Um there was this fancy

00:25:08.240 --> 00:25:09.990
architecture that allowed us to keep the

00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:11.430
whole thing in Python. So really

00:25:11.440 --> 00:25:13.669
hackable for researchers, but at the

00:25:13.679 --> 00:25:16.230
same time it had this vector database in

00:25:16.240 --> 00:25:17.909
the back end that you really didn't even

00:25:17.919 --> 00:25:19.350
have to care about. you could just write

00:25:19.360 --> 00:25:21.830
normal code and it was still able to run

00:25:21.840 --> 00:25:24.149
several thousand steps per second which

00:25:24.159 --> 00:25:25.990
was very fast at the time at the very

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:28.070
least. We also got the training to be

00:25:28.080 --> 00:25:29.669
much much faster than what else was out

00:25:29.679 --> 00:25:31.430
there at the time and we got it in a

00:25:31.440 --> 00:25:34.549
very very simple library uh which was

00:25:34.559 --> 00:25:35.830
quite difficult to do with an

00:25:35.840 --> 00:25:37.590
environment that has these properties.

00:25:37.600 --> 00:25:39.190
You know typically environments like

00:25:39.200 --> 00:25:41.190
this had these bespoke gigantic training

00:25:41.200 --> 00:25:43.110
code bases. So we got it down to just a

00:25:43.120 --> 00:25:44.950
few hundred lines of training code. uh

00:25:44.960 --> 00:25:47.190
with clean RL we actually were using the

00:25:47.200 --> 00:25:49.029
very very first version of puffer lib

00:25:49.039 --> 00:25:50.470
for this like when it was just in its

00:25:50.480 --> 00:25:52.870
infancy and this was kind of the first

00:25:52.880 --> 00:25:54.710
time that it all came together into

00:25:54.720 --> 00:25:56.870
something that seemed like a real useful

00:25:56.880 --> 00:25:59.590
awesome problem to study. I spent a

00:25:59.600 --> 00:26:01.750
bunch of my PhD running competitions on

00:26:01.760 --> 00:26:03.269
that version and then the versions

00:26:03.279 --> 00:26:05.110
leading up to that. So we'd go to

00:26:05.120 --> 00:26:07.669
conferences uh leading up to conferences

00:26:07.679 --> 00:26:09.510
we would challenge people to train

00:26:09.520 --> 00:26:11.830
agents on neural MMO. These ended up

00:26:11.840 --> 00:26:13.669
being very popular. So we ran one at

00:26:13.679 --> 00:26:15.830
Ichkai, we ran one at Nuruk the next

00:26:15.840 --> 00:26:17.830
year that ended up being I believe the

00:26:17.840 --> 00:26:20.789
largest competition in RL that year and

00:26:20.799 --> 00:26:24.310
then we had an additional one in 2023 on

00:26:24.320 --> 00:26:26.470
2.0.

00:26:26.480 --> 00:26:28.149
And the idea was that you would train an

00:26:28.159 --> 00:26:29.750
agent or train a team of agents. We'd

00:26:29.760 --> 00:26:31.350
take everybody's agents, we'd stick them

00:26:31.360 --> 00:26:33.029
all into the same environment and we'd

00:26:33.039 --> 00:26:34.630
see how they do against each other on

00:26:34.640 --> 00:26:37.190
various different tasks.

00:26:37.200 --> 00:26:39.029
And it was pretty cool because quite

00:26:39.039 --> 00:26:40.390
quickly we would see different

00:26:40.400 --> 00:26:42.070
participants agents learning different

00:26:42.080 --> 00:26:45.029
strategies um just by virtue of

00:26:45.039 --> 00:26:46.630
differences in the approach the authors

00:26:46.640 --> 00:26:48.710
had taken not necessarily attempting to

00:26:48.720 --> 00:26:50.870
incentivize one specific strategy. There

00:26:50.880 --> 00:26:52.470
was just a lot of diversity in the

00:26:52.480 --> 00:26:54.390
environment itself as to what approaches

00:26:54.400 --> 00:26:56.390
were viable. So we would see some agents

00:26:56.400 --> 00:26:58.230
that would like explore around the outer

00:26:58.240 --> 00:26:59.990
section of the map. We'd see some agents

00:27:00.000 --> 00:27:01.909
in teams that would play split. Some

00:27:01.919 --> 00:27:03.510
would play very close together. Some

00:27:03.520 --> 00:27:05.750
would like break off into two sub teams.

00:27:05.760 --> 00:27:08.789
quite a lot of strategic diversity.

00:27:08.799 --> 00:27:10.470
In one of the later competitions, we

00:27:10.480 --> 00:27:12.149
decided we decided that it should be

00:27:12.159 --> 00:27:14.070
more like a battle royale type thing

00:27:14.080 --> 00:27:16.070
where it was the last one standing wins

00:27:16.080 --> 00:27:17.750
because this gave you a very very clear

00:27:17.760 --> 00:27:20.149
objective. And we ended up seeing some

00:27:20.159 --> 00:27:22.710
of the strategies emerge that we see

00:27:22.720 --> 00:27:25.110
players using, human players using in

00:27:25.120 --> 00:27:27.350
actual battle royale games. So, in that

00:27:27.360 --> 00:27:28.710
genre, there's almost always something

00:27:28.720 --> 00:27:30.789
that pushes you towards the center by

00:27:30.799 --> 00:27:33.110
inflicting damage on you over time. And

00:27:33.120 --> 00:27:34.630
one things that you'll see players do is

00:27:34.640 --> 00:27:36.549
if they can, if the game allows for it,

00:27:36.559 --> 00:27:38.070
they'll just kind of stand there for a

00:27:38.080 --> 00:27:40.070
while and tank the damage so that they

00:27:40.080 --> 00:27:41.990
let everybody else fight and then they

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:44.149
can kind of come in at the end and just

00:27:44.159 --> 00:27:45.750
take out the last couple people that are

00:27:45.760 --> 00:27:47.830
pretty weak. And the agents learn to do

00:27:47.840 --> 00:27:49.350
that. Lo and behold, and they learn to

00:27:49.360 --> 00:27:50.470
do a bunch of other things that we see

00:27:50.480 --> 00:27:52.870
in that genre as well. So that was super

00:27:52.880 --> 00:27:55.110
cool to see.

00:27:55.120 --> 00:27:57.110
Early on in competitions, a lot of

00:27:57.120 --> 00:27:58.630
people were submitting scripted agents

00:27:58.640 --> 00:28:00.470
that were pretty good and competitive.

00:28:00.480 --> 00:28:02.630
But by the end of it, we actually had

00:28:02.640 --> 00:28:03.909
all the reinforcement learning

00:28:03.919 --> 00:28:05.669
approaches just being way, way better.

00:28:05.679 --> 00:28:07.590
So this was also in line with what we

00:28:07.600 --> 00:28:09.190
expected. Takes a little bit of time to

00:28:09.200 --> 00:28:11.190
get RL up in one running, but when you

00:28:11.200 --> 00:28:14.070
do, you can't compete with it.

00:28:14.080 --> 00:28:16.870
So from my PhD overall, I expected to go

00:28:16.880 --> 00:28:18.630
in having to come up with a bunch of new

00:28:18.640 --> 00:28:21.269
fancy algorithms in order to study the

00:28:21.279 --> 00:28:23.350
types of things that we wanted. But it

00:28:23.360 --> 00:28:24.789
turns out that the base algorithm that

00:28:24.799 --> 00:28:26.389
we were using and most people were using

00:28:26.399 --> 00:28:28.950
of PO was just very very effective even

00:28:28.960 --> 00:28:31.750
at small scale. And the main barrier was

00:28:31.760 --> 00:28:33.669
just not being able to study the right

00:28:33.679 --> 00:28:35.750
problems, not having interpretability,

00:28:35.760 --> 00:28:37.029
not knowing how to build efficient

00:28:37.039 --> 00:28:38.950
simulations, like a completely different

00:28:38.960 --> 00:28:40.389
set of problems from what most people

00:28:40.399 --> 00:28:42.070
were looking at ended up being the major

00:28:42.080 --> 00:28:44.230
bottleneck. And neural MMO ended up

00:28:44.240 --> 00:28:45.830
being both a very good environment for

00:28:45.840 --> 00:28:47.750
figuring this out as well as a playbook

00:28:47.760 --> 00:28:50.630
for building simulations in the future.

00:28:50.640 --> 00:28:53.110
which then brings me to what I spent my

00:28:53.120 --> 00:28:54.630
time doing in the last couple years

00:28:54.640 --> 00:28:56.710
after my PhD.

00:28:56.720 --> 00:28:59.990
So, we had all this working. Um, but it

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:01.510
wasn't everywhere yet, right? We kind of

00:29:01.520 --> 00:29:03.350
knew what to do, but we didn't know how

00:29:03.360 --> 00:29:05.669
to quickly make RL work in a variety of

00:29:05.679 --> 00:29:07.190
settings yet. We kind of had the

00:29:07.200 --> 00:29:08.950
playbook, but we didn't have all the

00:29:08.960 --> 00:29:11.590
infrastructure and stuff set up. So the

00:29:11.600 --> 00:29:13.110
very first thing I did after graduating

00:29:13.120 --> 00:29:15.430
was to uh create these really simple

00:29:15.440 --> 00:29:16.710
wrappers using what I'd learned from

00:29:16.720 --> 00:29:18.789
neural MMO that would let you take

00:29:18.799 --> 00:29:20.950
neural MMO or net hack or basically any

00:29:20.960 --> 00:29:23.750
other environment and just run it with

00:29:23.760 --> 00:29:25.750
the simplest tools out there. So the

00:29:25.760 --> 00:29:27.430
idea is that instead of studying simple

00:29:27.440 --> 00:29:28.710
problems because you're constrained by

00:29:28.720 --> 00:29:30.389
infrastructure, you can study quite

00:29:30.399 --> 00:29:32.630
complex problems. And the idea with

00:29:32.640 --> 00:29:34.470
puffer lip was okay this will push RL

00:29:34.480 --> 00:29:36.230
towards more interesting problems and

00:29:36.240 --> 00:29:37.669
we'll see where we can go from there

00:29:37.679 --> 00:29:39.590
once we are able to get RL onto more

00:29:39.600 --> 00:29:41.669
interesting problems. Now the next thing

00:29:41.679 --> 00:29:43.830
is once you had this and once everything

00:29:43.840 --> 00:29:46.230
became a lot simpler the speed issue

00:29:46.240 --> 00:29:49.190
became very very clear and the first

00:29:49.200 --> 00:29:51.750
thing that I noticed was that actually a

00:29:51.760 --> 00:29:54.149
lot of the slowness of RL wasn't even

00:29:54.159 --> 00:29:56.149
coming from training it was coming from

00:29:56.159 --> 00:29:58.710
the environments and specifically you

00:29:58.720 --> 00:30:00.470
always run a bunch of copies of your

00:30:00.480 --> 00:30:02.470
environment on different processes and

00:30:02.480 --> 00:30:04.230
the multipprocessing backend that was

00:30:04.240 --> 00:30:06.070
used for this everywhere was just

00:30:06.080 --> 00:30:09.269
abysmally slow like often times just as

00:30:09.279 --> 00:30:11.269
slow as running it on one core. for

00:30:11.279 --> 00:30:12.710
especially for these more complex

00:30:12.720 --> 00:30:14.149
environments because they weren't built

00:30:14.159 --> 00:30:16.549
for that. So I wrote a new

00:30:16.559 --> 00:30:18.310
multipprocessing backend from the ground

00:30:18.320 --> 00:30:20.789
up using what I learned from puffer uh

00:30:20.799 --> 00:30:23.269
not from puffer from neural mo with this

00:30:23.279 --> 00:30:25.029
compatibility wrapper in mind what would

00:30:25.039 --> 00:30:27.269
work for everything. We eliminated a lot

00:30:27.279 --> 00:30:29.510
of redundancy a lot of overhead and

00:30:29.520 --> 00:30:31.350
immediately we got stuff like 10 times

00:30:31.360 --> 00:30:33.669
faster on a whole bunch of environments

00:30:33.679 --> 00:30:35.269
and even we got a reasonable speed

00:30:35.279 --> 00:30:36.789
bottleneck even on some of the standard

00:30:36.799 --> 00:30:37.830
environments where it should have been

00:30:37.840 --> 00:30:39.990
fast to begin with. So this was kind of

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:41.909
an eye openener because you're not

00:30:41.919 --> 00:30:43.510
supposed to be able to make stuff way

00:30:43.520 --> 00:30:45.990
way faster just easily. Like it's

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:48.230
supposed to be that stuff is pretty well

00:30:48.240 --> 00:30:50.389
optimized and if stuff isn't then that's

00:30:50.399 --> 00:30:52.230
like okay well what else is slow out

00:30:52.240 --> 00:30:53.990
there right? How much more can we do

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:56.389
just by making some stuff faster. So we

00:30:56.399 --> 00:30:58.789
realized that even after we did this the

00:30:58.799 --> 00:31:00.310
bottleneck still wasn't training it was

00:31:00.320 --> 00:31:02.870
still the environment simulation. So

00:31:02.880 --> 00:31:06.149
okay let's write some environments in C.

00:31:06.159 --> 00:31:08.070
Let's see how that goes. Now, it didn't

00:31:08.080 --> 00:31:09.510
really start off in C. First, it was S

00:31:09.520 --> 00:31:11.190
Python and then stuff got ported over to

00:31:11.200 --> 00:31:12.789
something else. But then eventually, we

00:31:12.799 --> 00:31:15.269
ended up in C. And I started streaming a

00:31:15.279 --> 00:31:16.630
lot of my development as well because I

00:31:16.640 --> 00:31:18.870
thought it would be fun. And uh as a

00:31:18.880 --> 00:31:20.149
result of this, I was kind of sitting

00:31:20.159 --> 00:31:22.470
there jamming on environments in C for

00:31:22.480 --> 00:31:24.389
research. And a bunch of people thought,

00:31:24.399 --> 00:31:25.830
"Oh, that looks like a fun project.

00:31:25.840 --> 00:31:27.590
Let's build some environments as well

00:31:27.600 --> 00:31:29.510
and contribute them." So this ended up

00:31:29.520 --> 00:31:31.350
being a big open source project in which

00:31:31.360 --> 00:31:33.110
we have tons and tons of people building

00:31:33.120 --> 00:31:34.950
these environments and they're directly

00:31:34.960 --> 00:31:37.430
useful to research because now we have a

00:31:37.440 --> 00:31:39.350
huge library of super super fast

00:31:39.360 --> 00:31:41.269
simulations and we can just test our

00:31:41.279 --> 00:31:43.669
reinforcement learning on all of them

00:31:43.679 --> 00:31:45.430
and in fact because they're in C you can

00:31:45.440 --> 00:31:47.110
compile them to web assembly they go

00:31:47.120 --> 00:31:49.750
right on the website in puffer.ai super

00:31:49.760 --> 00:31:52.950
easy and fast.

00:31:52.960 --> 00:31:55.509
So this just made everything way way

00:31:55.519 --> 00:31:56.710
faster. And there were additional

00:31:56.720 --> 00:31:58.389
optimizations I'm skipping over a little

00:31:58.399 --> 00:32:01.509
bit here, but I made a version of neural

00:32:01.519 --> 00:32:05.990
MMO as a followup to my PhD um in C and

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:07.830
using the new vectorzation, using the

00:32:07.840 --> 00:32:10.630
new stuff in Puffer Lib, and it got to

00:32:10.640 --> 00:32:12.310
like several hundred thousand steps per

00:32:12.320 --> 00:32:15.430
second training per GPU. Uh, and this

00:32:15.440 --> 00:32:17.029
meant that we could train on a thousand

00:32:17.039 --> 00:32:18.870
times more data than I could ever hope

00:32:18.880 --> 00:32:21.350
to have trained on during my PhD. So we

00:32:21.360 --> 00:32:24.389
were able to train a model on 12,000

00:32:24.399 --> 00:32:26.789
years worth of gameplay. That's 200 uh

00:32:26.799 --> 00:32:29.909
640 billion observations. So more than a

00:32:29.919 --> 00:32:31.750
pabyte. If you're thinking about

00:32:31.760 --> 00:32:33.590
language models these days is using a

00:32:33.600 --> 00:32:35.590
lot of data training on tens of

00:32:35.600 --> 00:32:38.070
trillions of tokens. So like you know

00:32:38.080 --> 00:32:41.110
tens to maybe hundred terabytes of data.

00:32:41.120 --> 00:32:43.190
Like look how much data we're using on

00:32:43.200 --> 00:32:46.630
one machine. It was just huge.

00:32:46.640 --> 00:32:48.310
And as a result, we were able to train

00:32:48.320 --> 00:32:49.909
agents with this nice log linear

00:32:49.919 --> 00:32:51.830
learning curve that actually were better

00:32:51.840 --> 00:32:53.430
than me at the game and I wrote the

00:32:53.440 --> 00:32:54.950
game. And they came up with some stuff

00:32:54.960 --> 00:32:56.870
in the game that I didn't expect to be

00:32:56.880 --> 00:32:58.710
possible when they programmed it in. And

00:32:58.720 --> 00:33:00.149
this is pretty much like the full neural

00:33:00.159 --> 00:33:02.470
MMO 2 as well. Pro arguably even more

00:33:02.480 --> 00:33:04.630
complex. There's skills that you can

00:33:04.640 --> 00:33:06.070
level up, different professions, their

00:33:06.080 --> 00:33:07.590
different items, equipment, there's a

00:33:07.600 --> 00:33:09.269
market, they can buy and sell stuff. And

00:33:09.279 --> 00:33:10.549
they figured out a lot of this stuff

00:33:10.559 --> 00:33:12.549
very, very well. and especially they

00:33:12.559 --> 00:33:14.149
figured out a lot of very mechanically

00:33:14.159 --> 00:33:15.909
difficult stuff to do with the combat as

00:33:15.919 --> 00:33:18.310
well.

00:33:18.320 --> 00:33:21.190
Now when you make stuff really fast um

00:33:21.200 --> 00:33:23.269
experimentation itself becomes a lot

00:33:23.279 --> 00:33:24.950
easier because you can simply run more

00:33:24.960 --> 00:33:27.190
experiments and one of the things that

00:33:27.200 --> 00:33:28.870
became very obvious is that the

00:33:28.880 --> 00:33:30.630
hyperparameters were a major major

00:33:30.640 --> 00:33:32.470
bottleneck in RL. You essentially have

00:33:32.480 --> 00:33:34.230
all these knobs you have to fiddle with.

00:33:34.240 --> 00:33:36.149
Um it's similar to other areas of AI.

00:33:36.159 --> 00:33:38.630
It's way way way harder and worse in RL

00:33:38.640 --> 00:33:40.230
I would say because you have a ton of

00:33:40.240 --> 00:33:41.909
different problems you're optimizing for

00:33:41.919 --> 00:33:44.710
not just one. And this was the next

00:33:44.720 --> 00:33:46.070
thing that we did is we made a really

00:33:46.080 --> 00:33:48.149
good hyperparameter sweep algorithm. We

00:33:48.159 --> 00:33:50.470
tested across everything. Lo and behold,

00:33:50.480 --> 00:33:52.549
this made it way easier to do research

00:33:52.559 --> 00:33:54.549
because now you actually have this whole

00:33:54.559 --> 00:33:56.789
problem of oh are my hyperparameters bad

00:33:56.799 --> 00:33:59.190
just goes out the window. we were able

00:33:59.200 --> 00:34:00.950
to make some core improvements to the

00:34:00.960 --> 00:34:03.350
learning algorithm as well that weren't

00:34:03.360 --> 00:34:05.350
like the crazy out there fancy new

00:34:05.360 --> 00:34:07.029
algorithm variety, right? It wasn't the

00:34:07.039 --> 00:34:08.310
type of thing that's going to be the

00:34:08.320 --> 00:34:10.310
genius new thing that you publish, but

00:34:10.320 --> 00:34:12.310
in practice when you evaluate them over

00:34:12.320 --> 00:34:13.990
all the environments, there's some

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:15.270
really really good stability

00:34:15.280 --> 00:34:17.270
improvements and they made us do a lot

00:34:17.280 --> 00:34:19.510
better on a lot of the environments. So

00:34:19.520 --> 00:34:22.230
we have articles on both of those and as

00:34:22.240 --> 00:34:24.710
a result of this just with speed and

00:34:24.720 --> 00:34:26.950
some small enhancements uh it's already

00:34:26.960 --> 00:34:28.550
at the point now where you can kind of

00:34:28.560 --> 00:34:30.869
just write up an environment run RL on

00:34:30.879 --> 00:34:32.790
it if it doesn't work run a sweep on it

00:34:32.800 --> 00:34:34.149
and you have it already working pretty

00:34:34.159 --> 00:34:35.510
much out of the box on small

00:34:35.520 --> 00:34:37.270
environments and if it doesn't work it's

00:34:37.280 --> 00:34:38.310
probably because the environment is

00:34:38.320 --> 00:34:40.389
wrong not the RL like you have a bug in

00:34:40.399 --> 00:34:42.149
there somewhere you know go play it a

00:34:42.159 --> 00:34:46.470
couple times see if it's messed up. Um,

00:34:46.480 --> 00:34:48.629
now I don't have slides for the stuff

00:34:48.639 --> 00:34:50.389
I'm doing now, but I'm going to spend a

00:34:50.399 --> 00:34:51.829
couple minutes talking about it before I

00:34:51.839 --> 00:34:56.069
take as many questions as you all have.

00:34:56.079 --> 00:34:57.829
What I've been doing for the last 6 to 8

00:34:57.839 --> 00:35:00.470
months is really going even deeper down

00:35:00.480 --> 00:35:02.550
that rabbit hole. Okay, we made RL a

00:35:02.560 --> 00:35:04.310
thousand times faster or 2,000 times

00:35:04.320 --> 00:35:07.270
faster, whatever it was. Uh, how much

00:35:07.280 --> 00:35:08.950
more can we go? Like what is the limit

00:35:08.960 --> 00:35:11.510
of the hardware? And it turns out we

00:35:11.520 --> 00:35:12.790
weren't even close to the limit of the

00:35:12.800 --> 00:35:15.510
hardware then at all. Uh it really was

00:35:15.520 --> 00:35:18.230
the case that from all the way from the

00:35:18.240 --> 00:35:21.430
environment down to the vectorzation the

00:35:21.440 --> 00:35:23.589
training implementations even into torch

00:35:23.599 --> 00:35:25.750
itself that we were using. Same problem

00:35:25.760 --> 00:35:27.349
with jacks by the way that doesn't fix

00:35:27.359 --> 00:35:29.990
it either. Uh everything was poorly

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:31.910
designed for this. So what we started

00:35:31.920 --> 00:35:33.670
doing is first of all I ported the

00:35:33.680 --> 00:35:36.150
Python training code into the torch C++

00:35:36.160 --> 00:35:38.710
API and I started writing some custom

00:35:38.720 --> 00:35:41.109
kernels. And at first it was just like,

00:35:41.119 --> 00:35:42.470
okay, these operations are kind of

00:35:42.480 --> 00:35:43.910
inefficient. Let's see if we can fuse

00:35:43.920 --> 00:35:45.990
some stuff. And we realized that torch

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:48.069
just has tons of little operations all

00:35:48.079 --> 00:35:49.910
over the place. It's death by a thousand

00:35:49.920 --> 00:35:51.670
cuts. So we started just fusing

00:35:51.680 --> 00:35:53.829
operations together. Uh we had more and

00:35:53.839 --> 00:35:55.510
more of the code in our custom kernels,

00:35:55.520 --> 00:35:57.670
not within torch. And the speed of

00:35:57.680 --> 00:35:59.190
training kept going up and up and up,

00:35:59.200 --> 00:36:00.790
right? It started at two or three

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:02.470
million and then it was very quickly at

00:36:02.480 --> 00:36:04.870
four or five, then it got to seven. We

00:36:04.880 --> 00:36:06.470
got some new contributors interested in

00:36:06.480 --> 00:36:08.069
the open- source side, helped on the

00:36:08.079 --> 00:36:09.990
multipprocosting back end that helped on

00:36:10.000 --> 00:36:12.150
some kernel optimizations. It got to

00:36:12.160 --> 00:36:14.870
nine, it got to 11. We got mixed

00:36:14.880 --> 00:36:16.310
precision training in there, which

00:36:16.320 --> 00:36:17.670
didn't work with torch because of the

00:36:17.680 --> 00:36:19.589
way their numeric are. And it got all

00:36:19.599 --> 00:36:21.990
the way up to 13 or 14 million steps per

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:23.430
second training, which is just

00:36:23.440 --> 00:36:25.510
completely unheard of, right? I don't

00:36:25.520 --> 00:36:26.790
think most people in RL would even

00:36:26.800 --> 00:36:28.710
consider that possible. And I've tried

00:36:28.720 --> 00:36:30.870
this on several different libraries and

00:36:30.880 --> 00:36:32.870
unless you're like massively cheating

00:36:32.880 --> 00:36:35.190
with the parameters and doing something

00:36:35.200 --> 00:36:36.790
like some completely impractical

00:36:36.800 --> 00:36:38.870
configuration, you can't get close to

00:36:38.880 --> 00:36:41.349
these speeds.

00:36:41.359 --> 00:36:42.630
But lo and behold, if you write it

00:36:42.640 --> 00:36:44.710
yourself, you can.

00:36:44.720 --> 00:36:46.390
Um,

00:36:46.400 --> 00:36:48.230
and then we looked at the code a couple

00:36:48.240 --> 00:36:50.390
weeks ago and realized, huh, Torch isn't

00:36:50.400 --> 00:36:51.750
actually doing all that much anymore.

00:36:51.760 --> 00:36:53.589
We've kind of shipped athesis in, right?

00:36:53.599 --> 00:36:55.030
Like every little thing that Torch was

00:36:55.040 --> 00:36:57.430
doing is now our own code replacing it.

00:36:57.440 --> 00:36:59.670
What if we just drop torch? So that's

00:36:59.680 --> 00:37:00.870
what I've been doing for the last couple

00:37:00.880 --> 00:37:02.470
of weeks. And it turns out it's actually

00:37:02.480 --> 00:37:05.030
very easy. And we only have a few

00:37:05.040 --> 00:37:07.430
hundred lines more code without Torch

00:37:07.440 --> 00:37:10.069
now than we previously did with Torch.

00:37:10.079 --> 00:37:12.150
So it wasn't even really saving us like

00:37:12.160 --> 00:37:14.230
a whole bunch of code at all. And it was

00:37:14.240 --> 00:37:16.470
losing all of that performance. And

00:37:16.480 --> 00:37:18.790
actually even worse, I think that having

00:37:18.800 --> 00:37:20.630
stuff slow obscures the way that you

00:37:20.640 --> 00:37:22.550
think about research because you're not

00:37:22.560 --> 00:37:24.870
actually thinking about architectures

00:37:24.880 --> 00:37:26.710
designed jointly with the hardware that

00:37:26.720 --> 00:37:28.310
you can run them on. You're not thinking

00:37:28.320 --> 00:37:30.550
about like performance per flop. You're

00:37:30.560 --> 00:37:32.470
thinking about performance for the

00:37:32.480 --> 00:37:34.790
specific really bad implementation of

00:37:34.800 --> 00:37:37.589
this architecture that you have. Um and

00:37:37.599 --> 00:37:39.510
in fact it can actually skew you to

00:37:39.520 --> 00:37:41.589
thinking about like oh you need a huge

00:37:41.599 --> 00:37:42.870
number of environments because it's

00:37:42.880 --> 00:37:44.790
inefficient on a smaller number of

00:37:44.800 --> 00:37:46.150
environments because the implementation

00:37:46.160 --> 00:37:48.390
is bad and in general it really like

00:37:48.400 --> 00:37:50.310
limits the set of efficient solutions

00:37:50.320 --> 00:37:52.150
that you have because of all the places

00:37:52.160 --> 00:37:54.550
where your code is inefficient. So

00:37:54.560 --> 00:37:55.829
really just thinking about this whole

00:37:55.839 --> 00:37:58.310
stack all the way up and down. The

00:37:58.320 --> 00:37:59.750
result of this is now we have a clear

00:37:59.760 --> 00:38:01.990
path forward for research. Uh we have

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:03.829
this working out of the box on a ton of

00:38:03.839 --> 00:38:06.069
problems. It's easier than ever for

00:38:06.079 --> 00:38:07.910
people to get involved in it. You don't

00:38:07.920 --> 00:38:09.270
need to learn a huge amount of things.

00:38:09.280 --> 00:38:10.630
You just need to learn a very small

00:38:10.640 --> 00:38:13.510
low-level toolkit. Um, you can run at

00:38:13.520 --> 00:38:15.990
home on a single GPU, even a very

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:17.829
low-end one. If you don't have one, you

00:38:17.839 --> 00:38:19.750
can rent one online for 5 cents an hour

00:38:19.760 --> 00:38:21.670
that will train faster than pretty much

00:38:21.680 --> 00:38:24.230
anything else out there.

00:38:24.240 --> 00:38:25.990
And the future of ARL is now very, very

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:27.349
bright. And what I'm going to be doing

00:38:27.359 --> 00:38:28.790
in the next few months is cleaning this

